</head>
<body><p>GE.12-14740 
</p>
<p><b>Human Rights Council 
Twentieth session 
</b></p>
<p>Agenda item 10 
</p>
<p><b>Technical assistance and capacity-building 
</b></p>
<p><b>  Australia
</b>*
<b>, Somalia
</b></p>
<p>*
<b>, Turkey
</b></p>
<p>*
<b>: draft resolution 
</b></p>
<p><b>  20</b>/&#8230;<b> Assistance to Somalia in the field of human rights 
</b></p>
<p><i>The Human Rights Council</i>, 
</p>
<p><i>Guided</i> by the Charter of the United Nations and the Universal Declaration of 
</p>
<p>Human Rights, and recalling General Assembly resolution 60/251 of 15 March 2006,   
</p>
<p><i>Acknowledging</i> that peace and security, development and human rights are the 
</p>
<p>pillars of the United Nations system,  
</p>
<p><i>Reaffirming</i> its respect for the sovereignty, territorial integrity, political 
</p>
<p>independence and unity of Somalia,  
</p>
<p><i>Recalling</i> Human Rights Council resolutions 5/1 and 5/2 of 18 June 2007 and 19/28 
</p>
<p>of 23 March 2012,  
</p>
<p><i>Acknowledging</i> the commitment of and efforts made by the African Union and the 
</p>
<p>Intergovernmental Authority on Development, and especially those of the African Union 
</p>
<p>Mission in Somalia, and recognizing those States contributing to the African Union 
</p>
<p>Mission in Somalia, including countries in the region, to support efforts to achieve security, 
</p>
<p>reconciliation and stability, and the efforts made by the international community and 
</p>
<p>regional stakeholders to help Somalia re-establish stability, peace and security on its 
</p>
<p>national territory,  
</p>
<p><i>Commending</i> the African Union Mission in Somalia for its efforts, as requested by 
</p>
<p>the Peace and Security Council, to minimize civilian casualties during its operations, 
</p>
<p>encouraging the Mission to intensify its efforts in this regard, and encouraging the African 
</p>
<p>Union to support the Mission in increasing awareness and training among its troops on 
</p>
<p>human rights and international humanitarian law, 
</p>
<p><i>Welcoming</i> the work of the Independent Expert on the situation of human rights in 
</p>
<p>Somalia, 
</p>
<p><i>Acknowledging</i> the constructive engagement of the Transitional Federal Government 
</p>
<p>and Somali regional authorities in the universal periodic review, 
</p>
<p>  
 *
</p>
<p> Non-Member State of the Human Rights Council. 
</p>

<p><i>Welcoming</i> the signing of the Memorandum of Understanding among the 
</p>
<p>Transitional Federal Government of Somalia, the Office of United Nations High 
</p>
<p>Commissioner for Human Rights and the United Nations Political Office for Somalia on 11 
</p>
<p>May 2012,  
</p>
<p><i>Deeply concerned</i> about the continuing violations and abuses perpetrated against 
</p>
<p>children by parties to the conflict, in particular in the most unstable regions of Somalia, 
</p>
<p>including the unlawful use and recruitment of child soldiers, and concerned about the 
</p>
<p>continued death, injury and displacement of children as a result of armed conflict, 
</p>
<p><i>Noting</i> that the political process in Somalia is at a critical phase, with only two 
</p>
<p>months left until the end of the transitional period on 20 August 2012, and looking towards 
</p>
<p>the transition to an elected government, 
</p>
<p><i>Warning</i> the would-be spoilers of the end of the ongoing transitional process against 
</p>
<p>sanctions, 
</p>
<p>1. <i>Expresses its continued serious concern</i> at the human rights and humanitarian 
</p>
<p>situation in Somalia;  
</p>
<p>2.<b> </b><i>Strongly condemns</i> the grave and systematic human rights abuses perpetrated 
</p>
<p>against the civilian population, in particular by Al-Shabaab and its affiliates, and calls for 
</p>
<p>their immediate cessation;  
</p>
<p>3.<b> </b><i>Calls on</i> Somalia to fulfil its obligations under international human rights law 
</p>
<p>and international humanitarian law;  
</p>
<p>4. <i>Emphasizes</i> that protecting, respecting and fulfilling human rights will be 
</p>
<p>essential for the legitimacy of any future Somali political leadership, and also emphasizes 
</p>
<p>the importance of training in human rights and international humanitarian law for Somali 
</p>
<p>security forces; 
</p>
<p>5. <i>Calls on </i>the Transitional Federal Government and any successor Government 
</p>
<p>to ensure the inclusion of human rights compliance mechanisms in instruments and 
</p>
<p>institutions at both the national and subnational levels, and to recognize the importance of 
</p>
<p>promoting and protecting human rights; <b> 
</b></p>
<p>6. <i>Calls on</i> the Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human 
</p>
<p>Rights to implement expeditiously the Memorandum of Understanding, and urges Member 
</p>
<p>States to support the Office of the High Commissioner and the efforts of the Somali 
</p>
<p>authorities at the national and subnational levels in this regard;  
</p>
<p>7. <i>Urges</i> all parties to facilitate rapid and unhindered humanitarian access, and 
</p>
<p>urges Member States to support tangibly the Somali authorities at the national and 
</p>
<p>subnational levels in delivering social services inter alia with the immediate deployment of 
</p>
<p>military engineering corps by the African Union Mission in Somalia and willing Member 
</p>
<p>States, recovery and development programmes in accordance with the peculiar needs of the 
</p>
<p>different regions as peace dividend; 
</p>
<p>8. <i>Encourages</i> the Transitional Federal Government and the African Union 
</p>
<p>Mission in Somalia to provide their security forces with training in international human 
</p>
<p>rights law and international humanitarian law, with the support of the international 
</p>
<p>community; 
</p>
<p>9. <i>Urges</i> all parties to take immediate steps to protect women and children and 
</p>
<p>to end abuses and violations committed against them, and calls, in particular, for an 
</p>
<p>immediate end to the unlawful recruitment and use of child soldiers; welcomes the efforts 
</p>
<p>of the Transitional Federal Government towards finalizing an action plan with the United 
</p>
<p>Nations to end the use of child soldiers and emphasizes the importance of signing and </p>


<p>implementing this plan immediately; and calls for the Transitional Federal Government, 
</p>
<p>relevant United Nations entities and others to strengthen child protection efforts, including 
</p>
<p>by ensuring that child protection efforts are appropriately resourced; concerned also about 
</p>
<p>abuses perpetrated against women in Somalia, including sexual violence, and emphasizing 
</p>
<p>accountability for all such abuses; 
</p>
<p>10. <i>Expresses deep concern</i> about continuing attacks against journalists in 
</p>
<p>Somalia, and urges all parties to refrain from intentional violence against and harassment of 
</p>
<p>journalists; 
</p>
<p>11. <i>Commends</i> Member States, such as Turkey, among others, that have 
</p>
<p>extended generous education assistance, and invites Member States to follow this example, 
</p>
<p>including through the provision of higher education programmes for Somali journalists to 
</p>
<p>boost the prominence of their role in the promotion of human rights through public 
</p>
<p>awareness campaigns in line with Human Rights Council resolution 10/32; 
</p>
<p>12.<b> </b><i>Decides</i> to extend the mandate of the Independent Expert on the situation of 
</p>
<p>human rights in Somalia for one year, from September 2012, with a view to maximizing the 
</p>
<p>provision and flow of technical assistance to Somalia in the field of human rights, in order 
</p>
<p>to support the efforts of the Transitional Federal Government and Somali subnational 
</p>
<p>authorities to ensure respect for human rights and strengthen the human rights regime in 
</p>
<p>preparation for the end of the transitional period on 20 August 2012, including in relation to 
</p>
<p>the presidential and parliamentary speaker elections, as well as other key tasks that must be 
</p>
<p>completed before this date, and to advise the Transitional Federal Government, the United 
</p>
<p>Nations and the international community as to the steps that need to be taken to ensure that 
</p>
<p>the environment is conducive to the free exchange of ideas and views and the conduct of 
</p>
<p>elections; and requests the Independent Expert to report to the Human Rights Council at its 
</p>
<p>twenty-fourth session on the situation of human rights and the implementation of technical 
</p>
<p>cooperation in Somalia; 
</p>
<p>13. <i>Urges<b></b></i><b> </b>the special procedure system and the thematic mandate holders to fully 
</p>
<p>engage and coordinate with the Independent Expert on the situation of human rights in 
</p>
<p>Somalia; 
</p>
<p>14. <i>Requests</i> the Office of the High Commissioner to provide the Independent 
</p>
<p>Expert with all the human, technical and financial assistance necessary to carry out his 
</p>
<p>mandate;  
</p>
<p>15. <i>Calls on</i> all parties to ensure that the progress made at the London 
</p>
<p>Conference on Somalia, held on 23 February 2012, is consolidated through effective action, 
</p>
<p>and to redouble their efforts to support the people of Somalia in their search for a better 
</p>
<p>future for their country;  
</p>
<p>16. <i>Welcomes</i> the outcomes of the second Istanbul Conference on Somalia, held 
</p>
<p>on 31 May and 1 June 2012, in particular those that reiterate that respect for human rights 
</p>
<p>must be at the heart of the peace process and that call on the Somali authorities to follow 
</p>
<p>through with their commitment to uphold human rights and the rule of law and to put an 
</p>
<p>end to the culture of violence and impunity;  
</p>
<p>17. <i>Also welcomes</i> the efforts of the Government of Italy in holding the meeting 
</p>
<p>of the International Contact Group on Somalia in Rome on 2 and 3 July 2012;<b> 
</b></p>
<p>18. <i>Further welcomes</i> the statements made by the President of the Security 
</p>
<p>Council on 5 March 2012 and 15 May 2012;  
</p>
<p>19. <i>Decides</i> to remain seized of the matter. 
</p>
<p>    </p>

</body></html>